  "prompt": "How can you determine the ionic charge of sodium?",
  "response": "To determine the ionic charge of sodium, you can follow these steps:\n\n1. Look at sodium's position on the periodic table:\n- Sodium is in Group 1 (alkali metals)\n- It has an atomic number of 11\n\n2. Consider electron configuration:\n- Sodium has 11 electrons\n- Its electron configuration is 1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076 3s\u00b9\n- It wants to lose its single outer electron to achieve a stable electron configuration\n\n3. Electron loss:\n- Sodium tends to lose its 3s\u00b9 electron\n- When it loses this electron, it becomes a positively charged ion\n\n4. Determine ionic charge:\n- By losing one electron, sodium forms Na\u207a (sodium ion)\n- The charge is +1\n\nKey points:\n- Sodium typically forms a +1 ionic charge\n- It loses one electron to become more stable\n- The Na\u207a ion has 10 electrons and a noble gas electron configuration\n- This makes it chemically stable\n\nSo, the ionic charge of sodium is +1 (Na\u207a).",
